The paper discusses the problem of acquiring abilities in the absence of a task-oriented reward function, which is a common problem in reinforcement learning. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) or artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also proposes a new approach to skill discovery, which involves exploring and learning skills that cover a wide range of states. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the robotics (cs.RO) or systems and control (cs.SY) sub-categories, as these fields often involve developing algorithms for controlling and navigating robots. Finally, the paper evaluates its approach on controlled environments, which suggests that it may also belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category, as computer vision often involves evaluating algorithms on visual tasks in controlled environments.
